COROLLARY.

From the two preceding lemmata three things may opportunely be noted.

One is: not even with an infinitely small distance be- ’ tween them can two straights inclose a space.

The reason is, because (just as in Lemma I) either each of them with the two common extreme points fixed can be revolved into occupying a new position, and so (from the definition of the straight line already given) neither will be a straight line: or only one remains in the same place, and so it alone is a straight line.

But that both cannot remain in the same place, while they inclose any space, even if infinitely little, will be manifest from considering that a face of the plane, in which the two are, can be converted from upper to lower, the two extreme points withal remaining in the same place.

Another is: nor moreover can any straight line, in any direct production of it, split into tw0, although with an interval infinitely small.
